explanation:
OS_SymbolLookup_Impl — The low-level implementation called by the target. Must be inspected to see whether and how SymbolName or SymbolAddress are passed to any string.h functions or otherwise accessed beyond bounds.

OS_SymbolLookup_Static — The static-table fallback used when the Impl call fails. Must be inspected to determine whether it scans or copies SymbolName or symbol-table strings and whether any string.h functions are used unsafely.

OS_GenericSymbolLookup_Impl — A callee of OS_SymbolLookup_Impl (per the call graph) that may perform string comparisons/copies; include to trace any string.h usage coming from the Impl path.

OS_ModuleSymbolLookup_Impl — Another callee of OS_SymbolLookup_Impl that may perform module-level symbol searching and string operations; include to check for out-of-bounds string accesses.

OS_CHECK_POINTER — Macro/function used at the top of OS_SymbolLookup to validate pointers. Its behavior (e.g., null-check only or additional dereferences/formatting) affects whether SymbolName can be safely used later.

cpuaddr — Type of SymbolAddress. Needed to know the pointed-to object type/size/representation so any writes/reads to *SymbolAddress (or assumptions about it) can be evaluated for bounds safety.

int32 — Return type used for error codes. Needed to interpret return values and conditional logic (OS_SUCCESS comparisons) that affect which code paths (and thus which string operations) execute.

OS_SUCCESS — The success constant compared against return codes. Required to understand the branch that triggers the static lookup and thereby which string operations may run.

OS_static_symbol_table, OS_static_symbol_count, OS_static_symbol_entry — The static symbol-table data structures that OS_SymbolLookup_Static will use. Their layout and string-storage scheme (owned buffers, lengths) are required to determine whether reads/copies/searches of symbol names can overrun buffers.

memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, strspn — The standard <string.h> functions covered by the MISRA rule. Include these symbols so the implementations listed above can be inspected for any calls to these functions and the exact argument expressions/lengths used (to detect potential out-of-bounds accesses).

OS_printf — Present in the call graph and possibly invoked by OS_CHECK_POINTER or error paths; any formatting or string-handling it does with SymbolName should be checked to ensure it does not cause out-of-bounds reads (e.g., via malformed format strings or assumptions about NUL-termination).

Rationale: To determine compliance with the MISRA rule we must examine not only the target wrapper but also all reachable implementations and data structures that manipulate SymbolName / symbol-table strings, plus the standard string functions they call. The symbols above cover the direct callees, their likely sub-call targets that perform string processing, pointer/type definitions and constants that control flow, and the standard library functions the rule targets.
